	<node ID="ID_1599241839" TEXT="Introduction to XML#$D$#">
		<node ID="ID_685971034" LINK="https://www.w3schools.com/XML/xml_whatis.asp" TEXT="Introduction to XML - w3schools.com">
			<node ID="ID_1032240987" TEXT="XML Does Not DO Anything. Maybe it is a little hard to understand but XML does not DO anything. This note is a note to Tove from Jani stored as XML:" />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_1946197847" LINK="https://www.ibm.com/developerworks/xml/tutorials/xmlintro/xmlintro.html" TEXT="Introduction to XML - ibm.com">
			<node ID="ID_471348972" TEXT="Introduction. XML or Extensible Markup Language is a markup language that you can use to create your own tags. It was created by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) to overcome the limitations of HTML the Hypertext Markup Language that is the basis for all Web pages. Like HTML XML is based on SGML -- Standard Generalized Markup Language." />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_618084593" LINK="https://www.stat.berkeley.edu/~nolan/stat133/Fall05/lectures/introXML.pdf" TEXT="Introduction to XML - Department of Statistics">
			<node ID="ID_800619043" TEXT="INTRODUCTION TO XML The bene&#64257;ts of using tabular ASCII &#64257;les are easy to see. &#8226; We can edit them in simple text editors. &#8226; There is a natural connection between the visual layout in the &#64257;le and the way we think about the dataset when computing on it." />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_611341006" LINK="https://www.sitepoint.com/really-good-introduction-xml/" TEXT="A Really Really Really Good Introduction to XML &#8212; SitePoint">
			<node ID="ID_1859903792" TEXT="Back in Chapter 1 Introduction to XML we talked a little bit about entities. An entity is a piece of XML code that can be used (and reused) in a document with an entity reference." />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_648579412" LINK="https://beginnersbook.com/2018/10/xml-introduction/" TEXT="Introduction to XML - BeginnersBook">
			<node ID="ID_1189370509" TEXT="Introduction to XML. By Chaitanya Singh | Filed Under: XML Tutorial. XML stands for eXtensible Markup Language and it is used for storing and transferring data. In this guide we will learn about XML. What is XML? XML is a markup language which is used for storing and transporting data. XML doesn&#8217;t depend on the platform and the software " />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_106608204" LINK="https://www.xmlfiles.com/xml/xml-intro/" TEXT="XML Introduction - XML Files">
			<node ID="ID_1440825559" TEXT="Introduction to XML What you should already know Before you continue you should have some basic understanding of the following: WWW HTML and the basics of building Web pages Web scripting languages like JavaScript and VBScript If you want to study these subjects Go To W3Schools. What is XML? XML stands for EXtensible Markup Language &#8230;" />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_530451523" LINK="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/XML/XML_introduction" TEXT="XML introduction - XML: Extensible Markup Language | MDN">
			<node ID="ID_1676422697" TEXT="XML (Extensible Markup Language) is a markup language similar to HTML but without predefined tags to use.Instead you define your own tags designed specifically for your needs. This is a powerful way to store data in a format that can be stored searched and shared." />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_1954010714" LINK="https://www.w3schools.com/xml/xml_usedfor.asp" TEXT="XML Usage - w3schools.com">
			<node ID="ID_1885584818" TEXT="XML Separates Data from Presentation. XML does not carry any information about how to be displayed. The same XML data can be used in many different presentation scenarios. Because of this with XML there is a full separation between data and presentation." />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_1586571910" LINK="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/xml/index.htm" TEXT="XML Tutorial - Tutorialspoint">
			<node ID="ID_364089705" TEXT="XML stands for Extensible Markup Language and is a text-based markup language derived from Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML).This tutorial will teach you the basics of XML. The tutorial is divided into sections such as XML Basics Advanced XML and XML tools." />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_753915065" LINK="https://www.slideshare.net/pohjus/introduction-to-xml-presentation" TEXT="Introduction to XML - SlideShare">
			<node ID="ID_348551081" TEXT="Introduction to XML Jussi Pohjolainen TAMK University of Applied Sciences Slideshare uses cookies to improve functionality and performance and to provide you with relevant advertising. If you continue browsing the site you agree to the use of cookies on this website." />
			</node>
		<node ID="ID_249665626" LINK="http://archive.oreilly.com/oreillyschool/courses/introxml/Introduction%20to%20XML%20v1.pdf" TEXT="Introduction to XML - OReilly">
			<node ID="ID_1387242252" TEXT="Introduction to XML Welcome to OSTs Introduction to XML course! In this course you will learn the fundamentals of XML for use with XML-enabled applications or general web use. Course Objectives When you complete this course you will be able to: demonstrate knowledge of XML SGML and HTML. find and fix syntax errors in XML elements and " />
			</node>
